                                <p> We have seen a lot of action in the fixed income investment market last month.</p>
								<ul>
									<li>Post office savings interest rates went up from 3.5% to 4% and one year term deposit now earns 7.7% </li><br />
									<li>NSC maturity reduced from 6 years to 5 years </li><br />
									<li>A popular investment vehicle Kisan Vikas Patra has been discontinued </li><br />
									<li>The common man’s retirement fund the Public Provident Fund will accept Rs. 1 lac every year from 1st Dec 2011 onward and will earn 8.6% from the coming year </li><br />
									<li>Banks are now free to fix their own interest rate for savings bank account</li><br />
									<li>The interest rate cycle seems to be peaking and FDs are offered at very attractive rates </li><br />
									<li>Even the tax saving infra bonds which were traditionally giving 5% - 6% are now offering up to 9% </li><br />
									<li>If interest rates fall the bond markets are likely to rally in the next six months say experts </li><br />
								</ul>
                                
                                <p>There is a scramble for activity to invest in debt, but you know what? Your Post office agent who would come and pester you for the annual Rs.70000 investment in PPF is not even picking your call these days. Heard that their commissions have been discontinued/slashed?</p>
                                
                                <p><strong>So, how should the investing public react to such news?</strong></p>
                                <p>Stock markets are testing new 24 month lows, the rupee is probably valued its cheapest in the recent years and gold as always is behaving crazy, shouldn’t you be liquidating all other investments and putting them in fixed deposits or short term bond funds?</p>
                                
                                <p><strong>Our Views on Fixed Income-</strong></p>
                                <p>"It is good that the government decided to increase interest rates for PO savings schemes. This could be advantageous for retail investors who invest predominantly in safe investments. However for our client members this had very little impact for two reasons - one, except for PPF, income from the other investments are taxable. For investors falling in the highest tax brackets the tax inefficiency of these investment will substantially bring down the net returns. Investors can max out their PPF investments.</p>
                                <p>Secondly, most of the PO investments have long maturity periods, atleast 5 years. The interest rates for these investments are also subject to changes in the long run. Also, usually in our planning process for long term goals, investments are in moderate to aggressive portfolios with a fair amount of exposure to equities. As we follow progressive asset allocation, it is close to impossible to rebalance portfolios with these investments.</p>
                                <p>Therefore, due to lack of flexibility, tax inefficiency and add to this, affected serviceability due to reduction in agent commission, we wouldn't recommend additional investments in PO schemes, except for PPF.</p>
                                <p>Investors will do well to keep their debt investments in short term debt mutual funds. If in the future, interest rates fall also, these funds will stand to gain. With tax free dividend options they are tax efficient also. Fixed deposits will also be good for investors falling in lower tax brackets."</p><br/>
                                
